The paper proposes a novel deep network architecture for vehicle Re-ID, which involves deep feature learning and generative adversarial network. This work mainly focuses on computer vision and machine learning, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves end-to-end training and deep feature embedding, which are common techniques in deep learning and could also indicate the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Moreover, the paper mentions the VeRi-776 and VehicleID datasets, which are commonly used in multimedia and multimedia systems research, suggesting that it could also belong to the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category. The paper also involves attribute-guided feature learning, which is a common technique in artificial intelligence, indicating that it could belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Finally, the paper addresses the issues of inter-class similarity and limited vehicle images, which are common challenges in cryptography and security research, suggesting that it could also belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category.
